Sentence: NbN is almost as important in superconducting applications as NbTi and has similar characteristics with a maximum transition temperature of 16 K [47], a short coherence length of 6.5 nm [48] and an upper critical field of 15 T [47].

This is probably due to a nitrogen deficiency in our material that causes a T c value intermediate between Nb (T c = 9.25 K [110] and stoichiometric NbN (T c = 16 K [47]) The transition is obviously much more continuous than in Pb-SBA-15 (shown in Fig. 2b) [8], which is likely a consequence of stronger fluctuations in the phase of the superconducting order parameter due to the shorter coherence length of NbN and thus a stronger 1D character of NbN-SBA-15.
In Fig. 4a, 1-F(T) (temperature dependence of the superconducting fraction in the sample) and dF/dT (T c distribution) are shown together with the corresponding data for Pb-SBA-15 (Fig. 4b) [8].
The inset of (a) shows a zoom on the magnetization data of NbN-SBA-15 and Pb-SBA-15 to show the onset of superconducting fluctuations in the high temperature regime. .
